The ancient Babylonians, furthermooe, constructed tables of squares and cubes. Such tables are found upon the famous tablets of Senkereh‚³ which are contemporary with the Ahmes papyrus. Application of these quadratic numbers to problems similar to those of Egypt already mentioned has not been dis- covered, but the fact is evident that such tables were a step toward the study of quadratic equations. Cantor4 shows that the ancient Hebrews were probably familiar with the 3, 4, 5 right triangle. In China, too, students mathematically inclined had come upon this number relation‚⁵ and evidently were studying quadratic numbers.
